> **APJ ABDUL KALAM TECHNOLOGICAL UNIVERSITY (KTU) | 2024 SCHEME**
> - **Course:** PBEOT404 - OBJECT ORIENTED PROGRAMMING USING JAVA
> - **Module:** Module 2
> - **Topic:** Object Oriented Programming in Java - Class Fundamentals

<!-- SECTION_1_START -->
## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

In the context of the **KTU 2024 Scheme (NEP 2020 aligned)** syllabus for *Object Oriented Programming using Java*, a **Class** is formally defined as a **blueprint**, **template**, or **user-defined prototype** from which objects are created. A class encapsulates data (attributes/fields) and behaviour (methods/functions) into a single logical unit. In Java, every program must reside within a class, making the class the fundamental building block of Java applications.

According to the **KTU 2024 Module 2** learning outcomes, students are expected to:
- **CO2**: Understand the principles of object-oriented programming such as data abstraction, encapsulation, inheritance, and polymorphism in Java.
- **CO3**: Develop Java programs using classes, objects, constructors, methods, and access control mechanisms.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Highlight:** A class in Java is a **reference type** (non-primitive data type) that combines **state** (fields), **behaviour** (methods), and **identity** (unique object address) into one cohesive structure. Mastery of class fundamentals is mandatory for the **End Semester Evaluation (ESE)** as it forms the foundation for inheritance, polymorphism, and exception handling covered in later modules.

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

Imagine you are an architect who designs houses. Before any house is built, you first draw a **blueprint**. This blueprint contains:
- **Specifications** → number of rooms, windows, doors (these are *fields/attributes*).
- **Functionalities** → the house can be opened, locked, painted (these are *methods/behaviours*).

Now, the blueprint itself is **not** a house. You cannot live in a blueprint. However, using this single blueprint, you can construct **many actual houses** (objects), each located at a different address (memory location), each potentially painted a different colour, but all conforming to the same structural plan.

In Java terminology:
- The **blueprint** = **Class**
- The **actual house** = **Object** (also called an *instance* of the class)
- **Specifications** = *Fields* (variables inside the class)
- **Functionalities** = *Methods* (functions inside the class)

> [!NOTE]
> **Key Intuition:** A class is a *logical entity* (no memory allocated at definition), while an object is a *physical entity* (memory allocated at instantiation). This distinction is a **favourite 3-mark question** in KTU board examinations.

### 1.3 Anatomy of a Java Class — The Class Declaration Syntax

The general structure of a Java class declaration follows this rigid syntax:

```java
[access_modifier] [non_access_modifier] class ClassName [extends ParentClass] [implements Interface1, Interface2, ...] {
    // Field declarations (state)

    // Constructor(s)

    // Method declarations (behaviour)

    // Inner class declarations (optional)
}
```

Where:
- **`access_modifier`** ∈ {`public`, `protected`, `private`, *package-private (default)*}
- **`non_access_modifier`** ∈ {`abstract`, `final`, `static`, `sealed`, `non-sealed`, `strictfp`}
- **`class`** is a **reserved keyword** in Java.
- **`extends`** denotes **single inheritance** (Java does NOT support multiple class inheritance).
- **`implements`** denotes **interface implementation** (Java supports multiple interface implementation).

> [!TIP]
> **KTU Board Pattern Tip:** The default access modifier (when none is specified) is called **package-private** or **default access**. It is *not* `public` and *not* `private`. Examiners specifically test whether students confuse these.

### 1.4 A Canonical Example — The `Student` Class

```java
public class Student {
    // ---- Fields (State) ----
    private String name;
    private int rollNumber;
    private double cgpa;

    // ---- Constructor (Initialisation) ----
    public Student(String name, int rollNumber, double cgpa) {
        this.name = name;
        this.rollNumber = rollNumber;
        this.cgpa = cgpa;
    }

    // ---- Method (Behaviour) ----
    public void displayDetails() {
        System.out.println("Name: " + name);
        System.out.println("Roll No: " + rollNumber);
        System.out.println("CGPA: " + cgpa);
    }
}
```

> [!NOTE]
> The `public` keyword on the class means the class is accessible from any other class. Note the file name `Student.java` *must* match the `public` class name — this is a **compilation rule**, not just a convention. Violating it results in: `error: class Student is public, should be declared in a file named Student.java`.

### 1.5 Standard Engineering Metrics in Class Design

| Metric | Standard Value | Justification |
|---|---|---|
| Maximum methods per class (industry guideline) | **~20–30** | Beyond this, **Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)** is violated. |
| Maximum lines per method | **~20–40** | Improves **readability**, **testability**, and **maintainability**. |
| Fields per class (recommended) | **<10** | High coupling smell — suggests refactoring. |
| Class name length | **PascalCase**, descriptive | Java naming convention enforced by IDEs. |
| Source file size | **<2000 lines** | Beyond this, the class should be decomposed. |

These metrics are **bolded** because they are industry-standard (Sun/Oracle Java Coding Conventions) and are referenced indirectly in KTU's *Software Engineering* course (PCT403).
<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

### 2.1 Classification of Class Members

A Java class is composed of two broad categories of members. Understanding this taxonomy is essential for both 3-mark and 14-mark KTU questions.

#### 2.1.1 Static Members (Class-Level)
- Belong to the **class itself**, not to any specific object.
- Stored in the **Method Area** (part of JVM memory) — only one copy exists, shared across all objects.
- Accessed using the syntax: `ClassName.memberName`.
- Memory is allocated when the class is **loaded** by the ClassLoader, not when objects are created.
- Example: `static int count;` and `static void display(){}`.

#### 2.1.2 Non-Static Members (Instance-Level)
- Belong to a **specific object** (instance).
- Stored in the **Heap Memory** — each object gets its own copy.
- Accessed using the syntax: `objectReference.memberName`.
- Memory is allocated for each object when `new` keyword is invoked.
- Example: `int rollNumber;` and `void displayDetails(){}`.

### 2.2 Detailed Breakdown of Class Components

#### 2.2.1 Fields (Instance Variables)
Fields are variables declared directly inside a class but outside any method, constructor, or block. They represent the **state** of an object.

```java
class Employee {
    String name;          // Instance field
    static String company; // Static field (class variable)
    final int id;         // Final instance field (must be initialised)
}
```

Field access control follows the **principle of encapsulation** — fields are typically declared `private` and accessed through `public` getter/setter methods (JavaBeans convention).

#### 2.2.2 Methods
Methods define the **behaviour** of a class. Java supports the following method categories:

| Method Type | Keyword | Caller | KTU Relevance |
|---|---|---|---|
| Instance method | *(none)* | object | Most common |
| Static method | `static` | Class or object | Tested in Module 2 |
| Abstract method | `abstract` | Subclass (must override) | Module 3 (Inheritance) |
| Final method | `final` | Cannot be overridden | Module 3 |
| Synchronized method | `synchronized` | Thread-safe | Advanced topic |

#### 2.2.3 Constructors
A constructor is a **special method** used to initialise a newly created object. Key rules:
- **Same name as the class** (case-sensitive).
- **No return type** (not even `void`).
- **Automatically invoked** when `new` is used.
- **Cannot be** `abstract`, `final`, `static`, or `synchronized`.
- If no constructor is defined, the compiler provides a **default no-arg constructor**.

#### 2.2.4 The `this` Keyword
The `this` keyword is a **reference variable** that refers to the **current object** — the one whose method or constructor is being called. Its primary uses are:

1. **Differentiating instance variables from local parameters** (most common).
2. **Invoking current object's methods** (implicit, rarely written explicitly).
3. **Invoking current class constructors** using `this()` and `this(arg1, arg2)`.
4. **Returning the current object** from a method (used in builder/fluent design patterns).
5. **Passing the current object as a parameter** to another method.

#### 2.2.5 Access Modifiers — Visibility Table

| Modifier | Same Class | Same Package | Subclass (Different Package) | Other Packages |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| `private` | ✅ Yes | ❌ No | ❌ No | ❌ No |
| *default* (package-private) | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | ❌ No | ❌ No |
| `protected` | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | ❌ No |
| `public` | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> This visibility matrix is a **high-yield 14-mark question** topic. KTU examiners often present partial tables and ask students to complete them. The `protected` row is the most commonly confused — note that it grants access to subclasses *even in different packages*, provided access is *through inheritance* (not via object reference).

#### 2.2.6 Non-Access Modifiers

| Modifier | Applicable To | Effect |
|---|---|---|
| `static` | Field, Method, Block, Inner class | Class-level member |
| `final` | Class, Method, Variable | Cannot be modified/overridden |
| `abstract` | Class, Method | Must be overridden (in subclass) |
| `synchronized` | Method, Block | Thread-safe access |
| `volatile` | Variable | Read from main memory (threads) |
| `transient` | Variable | Skipped during serialization |
| `native` | Method | Implemented in platform-dependent code (JNI) |
| `strictfp` | Class, Method | Strict floating-point calculations |

### 2.3 The Java Object Lifecycle — Memory Model

Understanding the lifecycle of a Java object is critical for KTU 14-mark derivations. The process is:

1. **Class Loading** → ClassLoader loads `.class` file into **Method Area**. Static variables get default values.
2. **Object Creation** → `new Student()` triggers:
    a. Memory allocation in **Heap** (size determined by instance fields).
    b. Default initialisation of instance fields (0, 0.0, false, null).
    c. Explicit initialisation (initialiser blocks, field assignments).
    d. Constructor execution.
3. **Object in Use** → Object is referenced by one or more variables; methods can be invoked.
4. **Object Unreferenced** → When all references are set to `null` or go out of scope, the object becomes eligible for **Garbage Collection (GC)**.
5. **Garbage Collection** → JVM's GC (typically a **Generational GC** using the *Mark-and-Sweep* algorithm) reclaims the heap memory. The `finalize()` method is called *once* before reclamation (deprecated since Java 9, removed in Java 18).

> [!NOTE]
> **Engineering Utility:** In real-time and embedded systems, deterministic memory management is critical. The **Java Real-Time Specification (RTSJ)** introduces `javax.realtime` package with `ScopedMemory` and `ImmortalMemory` to address GC pause times.

### 2.4 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| Concept | Formula / Rule | Memory Region | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| Object size | $S = \sum_{i=1}^{n} \text{size}(\text{field}_i) + \text{header} \approx 12\text{–}16 \text{ bytes}$ | Heap | Object header includes mark word + class pointer |
| Static memory | $M_{static} = \sum_{j=1}^{m} \text{size}(\text{staticField}_j)$ | Method Area | Allocated at class load |
| Reference size | $64 \text{ bits} = 8 \text{ bytes}$ (on 64-bit JVM with compressed oops: 4 bytes) | Stack/Heap | Pointer to object in heap |
| Garbage collection eligibility | $\text{Reachability} = 0 \text{ (no live references)}$ | Heap | Reachable from GC roots |
| Number of objects | $N = \frac{\text{Heap Size} - \text{Overhead}}{\text{Avg. Object Size}}$ | — | Theoretical maximum |
| Default field values | `int=0, double=0.0, boolean=false, char='\u0000', Object=null` | — | Compiler-injected |
| `this` keyword binding | `this \rightarrow \text{currentObject}` (immutable per call) | Stack | Hidden parameter |
| Method dispatch | $T_{\text{call}} = T_{\text{framePush}} + T_{\text{execute}} + T_{\text{framePop}}$ | Stack | Each method creates a stack frame |

> [!WARNING]
> The `|` (pipe) character is reserved in Markdown tables. In LaTeX expressions, use `\vert` or `\mid` instead of `|` to avoid table-breaking. KTU PDF rendering may fail silently if pipes leak.

### 2.5 Real-World Engineering Applications

1. **Domain Modelling in Enterprise Software:** Classes model real-world entities (e.g., `Customer`, `Order`, `Invoice` in an e-commerce platform). **Frameworks like Spring (Java)** rely heavily on POJO (Plain Old Java Object) classes.
2. **Android Development:** Every `Activity`, `Fragment`, and `ViewModel` is a class. UI components are objects instantiated from framework classes.
3. **Game Development:** Classes like `Player`, `Enemy`, `Weapon` are the foundation of any game engine (e.g., LibGDX, jMonkeyEngine).
4. **Distributed Systems (Microservices):** Each microservice is typically a Java class exposing REST endpoints via **Spring Boot**.
5. **Scientific Computing:** Classes encapsulate mathematical models (e.g., `Matrix`, `Vector`, `NeuralNetwork`) in libraries like **Apache Commons Math** and **Deeplearning4j**.

### 2.6 KTU 2024 Module 2 — Sub-Topics Coverage Map

| Class Fundamental | Sub-Topic | KTU Weightage |
|---|---|---|
| Class declaration | Syntax, access modifiers | ⭐⭐⭐ High |
| Objects & `new` keyword | Instantiation, memory | ⭐⭐⭐ High |
| Methods | Signature, overloading | ⭐⭐⭐ High |
| Constructors | Default, parameterized, copy | ⭐⭐⭐ High |
| `this` keyword | 5 use cases | ⭐⭐ Medium |
| `static` keyword | Class members | ⭐⭐⭐ High |
| Access control | Public, private, protected, default | ⭐⭐⭐ High |
| Wrapper classes | Autoboxing, unboxing | ⭐⭐ Medium |
| Garbage collection | `System.gc()`, `finalize()` | ⭐ Low |
| Nested classes | Inner, static nested, local, anonymous | ⭐⭐ Medium |
<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
## 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

### 3.1 Analytical Matrix: Complete Class Construction with All Members

Below is an **exhaustive, line-by-line analysis** of a fully-loaded class demonstrating every fundamental concept. This is the type of 14-mark answer KTU expects.

```java
// File: BankAccount.java
package com.ktu.banking;  // Package declaration (logical grouping)

public class BankAccount {

    // ===== 1. STATIC CONSTANTS =====
    public static final String BANK_NAME = "KTU National Bank";
    private static int accountCounter = 1000;  // Shared across all accounts

    // ===== 2. INSTANCE FIELDS (State) =====
    private final String accountNumber;   // Immutable after construction
    private String accountHolderName;
    private double balance;

    // ===== 3. STATIC INITIALISER BLOCK =====
    static {
        System.out.println("BankAccount class loaded into Method Area.");
        // Read config file, establish DB connection, etc.
    }

    // ===== 4. INSTANCE INITIALISER BLOCK =====
    {
        accountCounter++;  // Auto-increment counter for each new object
        System.out.println("Instance initialiser executed.");
    }

    // ===== 5. CONSTRUCTORS =====

    // 5a. Default constructor (no-arg)
    public BankAccount() {
        this("Unknown", 0.0);  // Constructor chaining via this()
    }

    // 5b. Parameterized constructor
    public BankAccount(String accountHolderName, double initialBalance) {
        this.accountNumber = BANK_NAME.substring(0, 3).toUpperCase() + "-" + accountCounter;
        this.accountHolderName = accountHolderName;
        if (initialBalance < 0) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Initial balance cannot be negative.");
        }
        this.balance = initialBalance;
        System.out.println("Account created: " + this.accountNumber);
    }

    // 5c. Copy constructor (user-defined, NOT provided by Java)
    public BankAccount(BankAccount other) {
        this.accountNumber = other.accountNumber;  // Same ID
        this.accountHolderName = other.accountHolderName;
        this.balance = other.balance;
    }

    // ===== 6. INSTANCE METHODS (Behaviour) =====
    public void deposit(double amount) {
        if (amount <= 0) {
            System.out.println("Invalid deposit amount.");
            return;
        }
        this.balance += amount;
        System.out.println("Deposited: " + amount + " | New Balance: " + this.balance);
    }

    public boolean withdraw(double amount) {
        if (amount > this.balance) {
            System.out.println("Insufficient funds.");
            return false;
        }
        this.balance -= amount;
        return true;
    }

    // ===== 7. GETTERS AND SETTERS (Encapsulation) =====
    public String getAccountNumber() { return this.accountNumber; }
    public String getAccountHolderName() { return this.accountHolderName; }
    public void setAccountHolderName(String name) { this.accountHolderName = name; }
    public double getBalance() { return this.balance; }

    // ===== 8. STATIC METHODS =====
    public static int getTotalAccounts() {
        return accountCounter - 1000;  // Number of accounts created
    }

    // ===== 9. METHOD OVERLOADING (Compile-time Polymorphism) =====
    public void display() {
        System.out.println(this.toString());
    }

    public void display(boolean showBalance) {
        System.out.println("Account: " + accountNumber + " | Holder: " + accountHolderName);
        if (showBalance) {
            System.out.println("Balance: " + balance);
        }
    }

    // ===== 10. toString() OVERRIDE =====
    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return "BankAccount[Number=" + accountNumber + 
               ", Holder=" + accountHolderName + 
               ", Balance=" + balance + "]";
    }
}
```

### 3.2 Step-by-Step Execution Walkthrough

#### Driver Class: `BankAccountDemo.java`

```java
public class BankAccountDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Step 1: Class loading
        // ClassLoader loads BankAccount.class into Method Area
        // Static variable accountCounter = 1000, BANK_NAME = "KTU National Bank"
        // Static initialiser block prints: "BankAccount class loaded into Method Area."

        // Step 2: First object creation
        BankAccount acc1 = new BankAccount("Alice", 5000.0);
        // Memory allocated in Heap (~32 bytes for 3 fields + header)
        // Default initialisation: accountNumber=null, accountHolderName=null, balance=0.0
        // Instance initialiser block: accountCounter becomes 1001
        // Constructor executes: accountNumber="KTU-1001", accountHolderName="Alice", balance=5000.0
        // Prints: "Account created: KTU-1001"

        // Step 3: Method invocation
        acc1.deposit(1500.0);  // balance becomes 6500.0
        acc1.withdraw(2000.0); // balance becomes 4500.0
        acc1.display(true);    // Prints full details

        // Step 4: Second object creation
        BankAccount acc2 = new BankAccount("Bob", 10000.0);
        // accountCounter becomes 1002
        // accountNumber="KTU-1002"

        // Step 5: Copy constructor
        BankAccount acc3 = new BankAccount(acc1);
        // acc3 is a new object with same state as acc1 but different memory address

        // Step 6: Static method call
        System.out.println("Total accounts: " + BankAccount.getTotalAccounts());
        // Output: "Total accounts: 2"
    }
}
```

#### Execution Trace Table

| Step | Action | Heap State | Method Area State | Output |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| 0 | Class loaded | — | `accountCounter=1000`, `BANK_NAME` | "BankAccount class loaded..." |
| 1 | `new BankAccount("Alice", 5000)` | `acc1@{addr1}` | `accountCounter=1001` | "Account created: KTU-1001" |
| 2 | `acc1.deposit(1500)` | `acc1.balance=6500` | (unchanged) | "Deposited: 1500.0..." |
| 3 | `acc1.withdraw(2000)` | `acc1.balance=4500` | (unchanged) | "Withdrew: 2000.0..." |
| 4 | `new BankAccount("Bob", 10000)` | `acc2@{addr2}` | `accountCounter=1002` | "Account created: KTU-1002" |
| 5 | `new BankAccount(acc1)` | `acc3@{addr3}` | (unchanged) | (copy, no print) |
| 6 | `BankAccount.getTotalAccounts()` | (unchanged) | returns `2` | "Total accounts: 2" |

### 3.3 Derivations for Constructor Chaining

Java enforces that **the first statement of any constructor must be either `this(...)` or `super(...)`** — and if neither is explicitly written, the compiler implicitly inserts `super();` (a call to the no-arg constructor of the parent class `Object`).

#### Derivation 3.3.1: Resolving Ambiguity with `this`

Consider the following scenario where field names and parameter names collide:

```java
public class Student {
    private String name;
    private int age;

    public Student(String name, int age) {
        // Without 'this', name = name is a no-op (assigns parameter to itself)
        this.name = name;  // 'this.name' = instance field, 'name' = parameter
        this.age = age;
    }
}
```

The `this.name` reference resolves to the **instance variable** of the current object, while the bare `name` reference resolves to the **method parameter** according to Java's *Variable Resolution Order* (most local scope wins):

$$
\text{Reference} \rightarrow \text{Local Variable} \rightarrow \text{Instance Variable} \rightarrow \text{Class Variable} \rightarrow \text{Inherited Variable}
$$

#### Derivation 3.3.2: Constructor Chaining Execution Order

For a hierarchy of chained constructors, the call stack unwinds from the most-derived constructor to the base constructor, then re-winds executing bodies:

```java
class A {
    A() { System.out.println("A()"); }
    A(int x) { this(); System.out.println("A(int): " + x); }
}
class B extends A {
    B() { this(10); System.out.println("B()"); }
    B(int x) { super(x); System.out.println("B(int): " + x); }
}
```

Execution sequence for `new B()`:

1. `B()` invoked → calls `this(10)` → `B(int)` invoked.
2. `B(int)` body starts → calls `super(x)` → `A(int)` invoked.
3. `A(int)` body starts → calls `this()` → `A()` invoked.
4. `A()` body executes → prints "A()".
5. Control returns to `A(int)` → prints "A(int): 10".
6. Control returns to `B(int)` → prints "B(int): 10".
7. Control returns to `B()` → prints "B()".

**Final Output:**
```
A()
A(int): 10
B(int): 10
B()
```

> [!NOTE]
> This output sequence is a **guaranteed KTU 14-mark question** topic. Students are expected to trace constructor chains and predict the exact output.

### 3.4 Garbage Collection Eligibility — Analytical Derivation

For a given object, **reachability** is determined by the JVM's **Mark Phase** starting from a set of **GC Roots**:

$$
\text{GC Roots} = \{\text{local variables on active stack frames},\ \text{active threads},\ \text{static fields},\ \text{JNI references}\}
$$

An object is **eligible for garbage collection** if and only if it is **not reachable** from any GC root.

**Example Analysis:**

```java
public void scopeDemo() {
    BankAccount a = new BankAccount("Alice", 5000);  // Object 1
    BankAccount b = new BankAccount("Bob", 3000);    // Object 2
    BankAccount c = new BankAccount("Charlie", 7000); // Object 3

    a = b;          // Object 1 loses reference → eligible for GC
    b = null;       // Object 2 still referenced by 'a' → NOT eligible
    c = a;          // Object 3 loses reference → eligible for GC
    // At this point: a and b point to Object 2; c also points to Object 2
    // Object 1 and Object 3 are eligible for GC
}
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Note that simply **making an object eligible for GC does NOT guarantee** its immediate collection. The JVM decides *when* to invoke the GC based on its algorithm (e.g., G1GC, ZGC, ParallelGC). You can *request* GC via `System.gc()` but the JVM is free to ignore it.

### 3.5 Overloading vs. Overriding — Compile-time vs. Runtime Resolution

Java distinguishes between two types of polymorphism. Class fundamentals focus on **overloading** (compile-time), which is resolved by the compiler based on method signature.

**Method Signature** = `methodName(parameterType1, parameterType2, ..., parameterTypeN)`

> [!NOTE]
> The **return type** is **NOT** part of the method signature. Two methods cannot have the same name and parameter list but different return types — this is a **compilation error**.

**Overloading Resolution Algorithm (Simplified):**

$$
\text{Resolve}(m, \text{args}) = \begin{cases} \text{Exact match} & \text{if } \exists\, m' \text{ with } \text{sig}(m') = \text{types}(\text{args}) \\ \text{Type promotion} & \text{char} \rightarrow \text{int},\ \text{float} \rightarrow \text{double},\ \text{int} \rightarrow \text{long} \\ \text{Autoboxing} & \text{int} \leftrightarrow \text{Integer},\ \text{double} \leftrightarrow \text{Double} \\ \text{Varargs} & \text{as last resort} \\ \text{Compile error} & \text{if no match} \end{cases}
$$
<!-- SECTION_3_END -->

