#### **Question A (14 Marks)**

**[KTU University Exam - Dec 2022]**

**(a)** Explain the different access specifiers available in Java with their visibility scope. Construct a class diagram for a `Library` system with members `title`, `author`, and `price` demonstrating appropriate access control. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write a Java program to implement a `Rectangle` class with private fields `length` and `width`. Include: (i) a default constructor, (ii) a parameterized constructor, (iii) a copy constructor, (iv) methods to compute area and perimeter, and (v) a `static` method to count the number of `Rectangle` objects created. Demonstrate the usage with a `main` method. **(7 marks)**

---

**Model Answer for Question A:**

**(a) Access Specifiers in Java (7 marks):**

Java provides **four** levels of access control through three explicit keywords plus the default (no keyword):

| Access Specifier | Same Class | Same Package | Subclass (Diff. Package) | Other Packages |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| `private` | ✅ | ❌ | ❌ | ❌ |
| *default* (package-private) | ✅ | ✅ | ❌ | ❌ |
| `protected` | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ (via inheritance) | ❌ |
| `public` | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ |

**Explanation:**

- **`private`**: The most restrictive. Members are accessible **only within the same class**. Used to enforce **encapsulation**.
- **Default (package-private)**: When no access modifier is specified. Members are accessible within the **same package** but not outside it. This is the **default access level**.
- **`protected`**: Members are accessible within the same package **AND** in subclasses (even if the subclass is in a different package). However, protected access from a different package works **only through inheritance** (i.e., via `this` or `super`, not via a parent object reference).
- **`public`**: The least restrictive. Members are accessible from **anywhere**, provided the class itself is accessible.

**Library Class Diagram (demonstrating access control):**

```java
package com.ktu.library;

public class Library {
    private String title;           // Hidden from outside world (encapsulation)
    private String author;
    private double price;
    private static int bookCount = 0;  // Shared class variable

    public Library() {                // Public constructor (universal access)
        this.title = "Untitled";
        this.author = "Anonymous";
        this.price = 0.0;
        bookCount++;
    }

    public Library(String title, String author, double price) {
        this.title = title;
        this.author = author;
        this.price = price;
        bookCount++;
    }

    // Protected method - accessible in subclasses in other packages
    protected void applyDiscount(double percent) {
        if (percent > 0 && percent <= 100) {
            this.price -= this.price * (percent / 100);
        }
    }

    // Default (package-private) method - accessible within same package
    void printSummary() {
        System.out.println(title + " by " + author);
    }

    // Public getters/setters - controlled external access
    public String getTitle() { return title; }
    public void setTitle(String title) { this.title = title; }
    public double getPrice() { return price; }

    public static int getBookCount() { return bookCount; }
}
```

