**Model Answer for Question B:**

**(a) Constructors in Java (7 marks):**

A **constructor** in Java is a **special member method** used to initialise an object at the time of its creation. It has the same name as the class and has **no return type** (not even `void`).

**Key Properties of Constructors:**
1. Same name as the class.
2. No return type declared.
3. Automatically invoked when an object is created using `new`.
4. Cannot be `abstract`, `final`, `static`, or `synchronized`.
5. If no constructor is explicitly defined, the compiler provides a **default no-arg constructor**.
6. Can be overloaded (multiple constructors with different parameter lists).
7. The first statement can be `this(...)` (constructor chaining) or `super(...)` (parent call).

**Types of Constructors:**

**1. Default (No-arg) Constructor:**
```java
class Car {
    String color;
    Car() {              // Default constructor
        color = "White";
    }
}
```

**2. Parameterized Constructor:**
```java
class Car {
    String color;
    Car(String c) {      // Parameterized constructor
        color = c;
    }
}
```

**3. Copy Constructor (User-defined, NOT in Java by default):**
```java
class Car {
    String color;
    Car(Car other) {     // Copy constructor
        this.color = other.color;
    }
}
```

**4. Private Constructor** (used in Singleton design pattern):
```java
class Singleton {
    private Singleton() {}  // Cannot be instantiated externally
}
```

**Constructor Overloading:**
Defining **multiple constructors** within the same class with **different parameter lists** (different number, type, or order of parameters) is called **constructor overloading**. It allows objects to be initialised in different ways.

```java
class Box {
    int length, width;

    Box() { length = 0; width = 0; }                           // No-arg
    Box(int side) { length = side; width = side; }             // Single-arg
    Box(int l, int w) { length = l; width = w; }               // Two-arg

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Box b1 = new Box();         // Calls no-arg
        Box b2 = new Box(5);        // Calls single-arg
        Box b3 = new Box(3, 4);     // Calls two-arg
    }
}
```

The compiler determines which constructor to invoke based on the arguments passed — this is **compile-time polymorphism**.

---

**(b) Code Output Prediction (7 marks):**

**Compilation Analysis:**

The code compiles successfully **without any errors**. The commented line `Line A` is commented out, so no error occurs. If uncommented, it would cause a compilation error: *"non-static variable x cannot be referenced from a static context"*.

**Step-by-Step Execution Trace:**

| Step | Operation | `t1.x` | `t2.x` | `y` (static) | Output |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| 0 | Class `Test` loaded | — | — | `0` (default) | — |
| 1 | `new Test(5)` → `t1` constructor | `5` | — | `1` (y++) | — |
| 2 | `new Test(10)` → `t2` constructor | `5` | `10` | `2` | — |
| 3 | `t1.increment()` → `x++` (t1), `y++` | `6` | `10` | `3` | — |
| 4 | `t2.increment()` → `x++` (t2), `y++` | `6` | `11` | `4` | — |
| 5 | `t2.increment()` → `x++` (t2), `y++` | `6` | `12` | `5` | — |
| 6 | `Test.showY()` | — | — | `5` | `y = 5` |
| 7 | Print t1.x, t2.x | `6` | `12` | — | `t1.x = 6, t2.x = 12` |
| 8 | Print t1.y, t2.y | — | — | `5` | `t1.y = 5, t2.y = 5` |

**Expected Final Output:**

```
y = 5
t1.x = 6, t2.x = 12
t1.y = 5, t2.y = 5
```

**Key Justification Points (for full marks):**

1. `y` is a **static variable**, so it is shared across all instances. After 2 constructor calls and 3 `increment()` calls, `y = 2 + 3 = 5`.
2. `x` is an **instance variable**, so each object has its own copy. `t1.x` started at 5 and was incremented once → 6. `t2.x` started at 10 and was incremented twice → 12.
3. `Test.showY()` is a **static method**, so it is invoked using the class name. It correctly accesses the static variable `y` but would fail if it tried to access the non-static `x` (which is why Line A is commented out).
4. `t1.y` and `t2.y` both print `5` because `y` is class-level, not instance-level. Accessing a static field through an object reference is allowed but discouraged (warning from IDE).

