### Question 2 [KTU University Exam - May 2024]

**Q: Explain the purpose of the `finally` block in Java. When does it not execute?**

**Model Answer:**

**Purpose:** The `finally` block in Java is used to execute **mandatory cleanup code** (such as closing files, database connections, releasing locks) regardless of whether an exception occurs or not. It is executed after the `try-catch` block completes.

**Syntax:**
```java
try {
    // risky code
} catch (Exception e) {
    // handling code
} finally {
    // cleanup code — always runs
}
```

**When `finally` does NOT execute:**
1. When `System.exit(0)` is explicitly called inside `try` or `catch`.
2. When the JVM crashes due to fatal errors (e.g., `StackOverflowError` causing termination).
3. When the thread executing the `try-catch-finally` is killed externally.
4. When an infinite loop or deadlock occurs inside `try`.

