## 5.3 KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout

> [!WARNING]
> **Common Mistakes that Lead to Mark Deduction:**
> 
> 1. **Confusing `throw` and `throws`**: Students often write `throws new Exception()` instead of `throw new Exception()`. Remember: `throw` needs an **instance**, `throws` needs a **class name**.
> 
> 2. **Writing code after `throw`**: Anything after `throw` in the same block becomes unreachable → compile-time error.
> 
> 3. **Forgetting `throws` declaration**: When a method calls another method that declares a checked exception via `throws`, the caller must either handle it or declare it again.
> 
> 4. **Wrong order of catch blocks**: Subclass exceptions must be caught **before** superclass exceptions.
> 
> 5. **Writing `return` in `finally` block**: This overrides the return value from `try-catch` and suppresses exceptions — a major logical bug.
> 
> 6. **Not using `finally` for resource cleanup**: Leads to resource leaks; KTU examiners look for `finally` blocks in file/DB handling programs.
> 
> 7. **Overriding with broader `throws`**: In method overriding, the subclass cannot throw a broader checked exception than the parent class.

---

## 5.4 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Rapid Revision Checklist:**

- ⭐ `throw` is used to **explicitly throw** an exception instance inside a method body.
- ⭐ `throws` is used to **declare** possible exceptions in the method signature.
- ⭐ `finally` block **always executes** (except in `System.exit(0)` or JVM crash scenarios).
- ⭐ A `try` block must be followed by at least one `catch` **OR** a `finally` block.
- ⭐ Multiple catch blocks can follow a single `try` block.
- ⭐ `throw` can throw only **one** exception at a time; `throws` can declare **multiple**.
- ⭐ Checked exceptions must be **handled or declared**; unchecked exceptions are optional.
- ⭐ Custom exceptions are created by extending `Exception` (checked) or `RuntimeException` (unchecked).
- ⭐ The overriding method **cannot throw broader checked exceptions** than the parent method.
- ⭐ `finally` block is ideal for closing files, database connections, and releasing locks.
- ⭐ Avoid `return` statements inside `finally` blocks to prevent logic errors.
- ⭐ The execution order in nested `try-catch-finally` is: **inner finally → outer catch → outer finally**.
- ⭐ Use `throw new ExceptionType("message")` for providing meaningful exception descriptions.
- ⭐ `getMessage()` retrieves the exception message; `printStackTrace()` prints full trace to console.
- ⭐ The `Throwable` class is the **root** of all exceptions and errors in Java.

