# SECTION 1: CORE TECHNICAL DEFINITION & INTUITIVE OVERVIEW

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition — JFrame

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Definition**
> **`JFrame`** is a top-level container class in the `javax.swing` package that extends `java.awt.Frame`. It represents a **standard window** with a title, border, and optional menu bar, used as the **primary building block** for any Swing-based Graphical User Interface (GUI) application. A `JFrame` can contain other Swing components such as buttons, text fields, labels, and panels, and it relies on the **Delegation Event Model** to handle user interactions.

The class signature is:
```java
public class JFrame extends Frame implements WindowConstants, Accessible, RootPaneContainer
```

## 1.2 Formal Academic Definition — Event Handling

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Definition**
> **Event Handling** is the mechanism by which a Java program responds to user actions (mouse clicks, key presses, window events, etc.) or system-generated actions. Swing follows the **Delegation Event Model (DEM)**, where an **Event Source** delegates the processing of an event to a registered **Event Listener**, which contains the **Event Handler** method.

## 1.3 Conceptual Analogy — The "TV Remote" Model

Imagine you bought a brand-new television. The **TV set** is the `JFrame` (the main window). The **remote control** is the **Event Listener** (e.g., `ActionListener`). Each **button on the remote** (Power, Volume+, Channel-) represents a different **Event Source** (e.g., `JButton`, `JTextField`). When you press a button on the remote, the TV reacts — this reaction is the **Event Handler method** (e.g., `actionPerformed()`).

The critical insight: **the TV doesn't know what to do unless the remote is registered with it**. Similarly, in Swing, a button does nothing until a listener is `addActionListener()`-ed to it. This registration process is the essence of the **Delegation Event Model**.

## 1.4 Key Terminology Table

| Term | Meaning | Swing Example |
|------|---------|---------------|
| **Event Source** | The component that generates an event | `JButton`, `JTextField` |
| **Event Object** | The object encapsulating event details | `ActionEvent`, `MouseEvent` |
| **Event Listener** | Interface defining handler methods | `ActionListener`, `MouseListener` |
| **Event Handler** | Method that executes when event occurs | `actionPerformed(ActionEvent e)` |
| **Delegation Model** | Source delegates event processing to listener | Standard Swing pattern |

> [!NOTE]
> **Syllabus Highlight:** KTU 2024 Scheme emphasizes that students must understand *why* Swing uses the Delegation Event Model instead of inheritance-based event handling (as in older AWT). The answer is **flexibility and loose coupling** — a single source can have multiple listeners, and listeners can be shared across multiple sources.

