# SECTION 2: DEEP THEORETICAL ANALYSIS & KTU HIGH-YIELD FORMULA SHEET

## 2.1 The Delegation Event Model — Step-by-Step Logic

The Delegation Event Model (DEM) is the **foundational architecture** of all Swing event handling. It operates in **four distinct phases**:

### Phase 1: Event Generation
A user performs an action (e.g., clicks a `JButton`). The **Event Source** detects the OS-level interrupt and creates an **Event Object** (e.g., `ActionEvent`) containing metadata such as:
- The source component
- The event ID
- Timestamp
- Modifier keys (Shift, Ctrl, Alt)

### Phase 2: Event Notification (Registration Phase)
The Event Source maintains an **internal listener registry** (typically a vector/list of listener references). When `addXXXListener()` is called, the listener object reference is appended to this registry.

### Phase 3: Event Dispatch
When the event occurs, the source **iterates** through its registered listener list and calls the appropriate handler method on each listener. This is automatic — the JVM uses **reflection** or **direct method invocation** depending on implementation.

### Phase 4: Event Handling
The listener's handler method executes. If the event is not consumed, it **propagates** to parent containers (for some event types like `KeyEvent`, `MouseEvent`).

> [!NOTE]
> **Why "Delegation"?** The source does **not** handle the event itself. It **delegates** the responsibility to external listener objects. This decouples the GUI component code from the business logic.

## 2.2 Event Types in Swing (Comprehensive Map)

| Event Class | Package | Triggered By | Listener Interface | Handler Method |
|-------------|---------|--------------|-------------------|----------------|
| `ActionEvent` | `java.awt.event` | Button click, menu selection, Enter in text field | `ActionListener` | `actionPerformed(ActionEvent)` |
| `MouseEvent` | `java.awt.event` | Mouse press, release, click, enter, exit | `MouseListener` | `mouseClicked/Pressed/Released/Entered/Exited` |
| `MouseEvent` (motion) | `java.awt.event` | Mouse moved, dragged | `MouseMotionListener` | `mouseMoved/MouseDragged` |
| `KeyEvent` | `java.awt.event` | Key press, release, type | `KeyListener` | `keyPressed/Typed/Released` |
| `WindowEvent` | `java.awt.event` | Window open, close, iconify | `WindowListener` | `windowOpened/Closing/Closed/Iconified/Deiconified/Activated/Deactivated` |
| `ItemEvent` | `java.awt.event` | Checkbox/radio toggle, list selection | `ItemListener` | `itemStateChanged(ItemEvent)` |
| `TextEvent` | `java.awt.event` | Text field value changed | `TextListener` | `textValueChanged(TextEvent)` |
| `FocusEvent` | `java.awt.event` | Component gains/loses focus | `FocusListener` | `focusGained/Lost` |

## 2.3 Adapter Classes — Solving the "Empty Method" Problem

Many listener interfaces (e.g., `MouseListener`) define **multiple methods**. If you only need `mouseClicked`, you must still provide empty implementations for the other 4 methods — which is verbose and error-prone.

**Solution:** Java provides **Adapter Classes** that implement the listener interface with **empty (no-op) method bodies**. You then override only the methods you need.

```java
public abstract class MouseAdapter implements MouseListener, MouseWheelListener {
    public void mouseClicked(MouseEvent e)  {}
    public void mousePressed(MouseEvent e)  {}
    public void mouseReleased(MouseEvent e) {}
    public void mouseEntered(MouseEvent e)  {}
    public void mouseExited(MouseEvent e)   {}
}
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Exam Tip:** Adapter classes exist ONLY for interfaces with **more than one method**. For interfaces with a single method (e.g., `ActionListener`, `ItemListener`), **no adapter class is provided** because lambda expressions can be used directly.

