## 3.2 Exhaustive Code Walkthrough #1 — Basic JFrame with ActionListener

**Problem:** Create a Swing application that displays a window with a button. When the button is clicked, display "Button Clicked!" on a label.

```java
// Step 1: Import required packages
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

// Step 2: Class implementing ActionListener interface
public class ButtonDemo extends JFrame implements ActionListener {

    // Step 3: Declare Swing components as instance variables
    JButton btn;
    JLabel lbl;

    // Step 4: Constructor — sets up the GUI
    ButtonDemo() {
        // Create components
        btn = new JButton("Click Me");
        lbl = new JLabel("                          ");

        // Set layout manager (FlowLayout = left-to-right)
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());

        // Add components to the frame's content pane
        add(btn);
        add(lbl);

        // Step 5: Register the listener with the event source
        btn.addActionListener(this);

        // Configure JFrame properties
        setTitle("My First Swing App");
        setSize(300, 150);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setVisible(true);
    }

    // Step 6: Implement the event handler method
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        lbl.setText("Button Clicked!");
    }

    // Step 7: Main method — entry point
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new ButtonDemo();
    }
}
```

### Logical Trace — What Happens When User Clicks the Button

1. **User clicks button** → OS sends hardware interrupt to JVM
2. **JVM** wraps it into an `ActionEvent` object: `e = new ActionEvent(btn, ACTION_PERFORMED, "Click Me")`
3. **JButton (event source)** iterates through its listener list
4. **Finds one listener** (the `ButtonDemo` instance, referenced as `this`)
5. **Invokes** `listener.actionPerformed(e)`
6. **Handler executes** → `lbl.setText("Button Clicked!")`
7. **Screen repaints** to show the new label text

## 3.3 Exhaustive Code Walkthrough #2 — Adapter Class with WindowListener

**Problem:** Create a JFrame that prints a message when the window is opened, and another when it is closing.

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class WindowDemo extends JFrame {

    WindowDemo() {
        setTitle("Window Adapter Demo");
        setSize(300, 200);

        // Register an anonymous WindowAdapter — overrides only needed methods
        addWindowListener(new WindowAdapter() {
            public void windowOpened(WindowEvent e) {
                System.out.println("Window Opened!");
            }
            public void windowClosing(WindowEvent e) {
                System.out.println("Window Closing!");
                System.exit(0);
            }
        });

        setVisible(true);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new WindowDemo();
    }
}
```

### Why Use an Adapter Here?

The `WindowListener` interface has **7 methods**. If we implemented it directly, we would need to write 7 empty methods. By extending `WindowAdapter`, we override only the 2 we need. This is the **KTU-recommended pattern** for verbose listener interfaces.

## 3.4 Exhaustive Code Walkthrough #3 — Multiple Event Sources, Single Listener

**Problem:** Create a calculator-style interface with two buttons (+ and -) and a label showing a counter value. The same listener handles both buttons.

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class CounterApp extends JFrame implements ActionListener {

    JButton btnPlus, btnMinus;
    JLabel lblCount;
    int count = 0;

    CounterApp() {
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());

        btnPlus  = new JButton("+");
        btnMinus = new JButton("-");
        lblCount = new JLabel("Count: 0");

        add(btnPlus);
        add(btnMinus);
        add(lblCount);

        // Step: Register the SAME listener with both buttons
        btnPlus.addActionListener(this);
        btnMinus.addActionListener(this);

        setTitle("Counter App");
        setSize(250, 100);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setVisible(true);
    }

    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        // Identify which button was clicked
        if (e.getSource() == btnPlus) {
            count++;
        } else if (e.getSource() == btnMinus) {
            count--;
        }
        lblCount.setText("Count: " + count);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new CounterApp();
    }
}
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Critical Method:** `e.getSource()` returns the **Object reference** of the component that fired the event. This is how a single listener method can distinguish between multiple registered sources. KTU board exams frequently test this.

## 3.5 Exhaustive Code Walkthrough #4 — Inner Class for Event Handling

**Problem:** Modify the counter application to use an **inner class** listener instead of implementing the interface in the outer class.

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class InnerClassDemo extends JFrame {

    JButton btn;
    JLabel lbl;
    int count = 0;

    InnerClassDemo() {
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());
        btn = new JButton("Increment");
        lbl = new JLabel("Count: 0");
        add(btn);
        add(lbl);

        // Register an anonymous inner class as the listener
        btn.addActionListener(new ActionListener() {
            public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
                count++;
                lbl.setText("Count: " + count);
            }
        });

        setTitle("Inner Class Demo");
        setSize(250, 100);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setVisible(true);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new InnerClassDemo();
    }
}
```

### Why Use Inner Classes?

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|----------|------|------|
| **Implementing interface in outer class** | Simple, all components accessible | Forces the class to implement the interface even for one button |
| **Inner class listener** | Encapsulated, can access outer class members | Slightly more verbose |
| **Anonymous inner class** | Concise, perfect for one-off handlers | Cannot be reused, harder to debug |
| **Lambda expression (Java 8+)** | Most concise syntax | Only works for **functional interfaces** (single method) |

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU 2024 Trend:** Recent board papers have started including **lambda expression** answers. The lambda equivalent of the anonymous inner class above is: `btn.addActionListener(e -> { count++; lbl.setText("Count: " + count); });`

