## 5.1 Part A Questions (3 Marks Each)

### Question 1: [KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]
**Explain the Delegation Event Model used in Java Swing with its main components.**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

The **Delegation Event Model (DEM)** is the standard event-handling mechanism in Java Swing where the responsibility of processing an event is **delegated** from the event source to a separate listener object.

**Three main components:**

1. **Event Source** — The GUI component (e.g., `JButton`, `JTextField`) that generates an event in response to user interaction. It maintains a list of registered listeners and notifies them when an event occurs.

2. **Event Object** — An object (e.g., `ActionEvent`, `MouseEvent`) that encapsulates all information about the event, such as the source component, event type, timestamp, and modifier keys. It is created by the source and passed to the listener.

3. **Event Listener** — An object that implements a listener interface (e.g., `ActionListener`) and contains the **event handler method** (e.g., `actionPerformed()`). The listener is registered with the source via `addXXXListener()` and is automatically invoked when the event occurs.

**Advantage:** This model provides **loose coupling** between the GUI component and the event-handling logic, allowing the same listener to be registered with multiple sources and enabling dynamic addition/removal of listeners at runtime. *(1 mark)*

---

### Question 2: [KTU University Exam - June 2024]
**What is the difference between an event listener interface and an event adapter class? Give one example of each.**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

| Aspect | Event Listener Interface | Event Adapter Class |
|--------|-------------------------|---------------------|
| **Definition** | An interface that defines one or more event-handler methods | An abstract class providing empty implementations of all methods in a listener interface |
| **Implementation** | The implementing class must override **all** abstract methods | The extending class can override **only the methods it needs** |
| **Purpose** | Defines the contract for event handling | Provides convenience to avoid boilerplate empty methods |
| **Example** | `MouseListener` (5 methods) | `MouseAdapter` (implements `MouseListener` with empty bodies) |
| **Example 2** | `KeyListener` (3 methods) | `KeyAdapter` |

**Key Point:** Adapter classes exist **only** for listener interfaces with **more than one abstract method**. For single-method interfaces like `ActionListener` and `ItemListener`, no adapter class is provided in the JDK. *(1 mark for example + difference)*

