## 3.1 Walkthrough 1: Basic JLabel with Text Only

### Problem Statement
Write a Java Swing program to create a `JFrame` containing a `JLabel` that displays the text *"Welcome to Java Swing Programming"* with a 24-point bold font, centered horizontally, and red foreground color.

### Solution Code

```java
import javax.swing.JFrame;
import javax.swing.JLabel;
import javax.swing.SwingConstants;
import java.awt.Color;
import java.awt.Font;

public class BasicLabelDemo extends JFrame {
    public BasicLabelDemo() {
        // Step 1: Create a JLabel with text
        JLabel welcomeLabel = new JLabel("Welcome to Java Swing Programming");

        // Step 2: Set the font — Arial, Bold, 24 points
        welcomeLabel.setFont(new Font("Arial", Font.BOLD, 24));

        // Step 3: Set horizontal alignment to CENTER
        welcomeLabel.setHorizontalAlignment(SwingConstants.CENTER);

        // Step 4: Set foreground (text) color to RED
        welcomeLabel.setForeground(Color.RED);

        // Step 5: Add label to the frame's content pane
        add(welcomeLabel);

        // Step 6: Configure the JFrame
        setTitle("Basic JLabel Demo");
        setSize(500, 150);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setLocationRelativeTo(null);   // Center on screen
        setVisible(true);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new BasicLabelDemo();
    }
}
```

### Analytical Matrix — Line-by-Line Reasoning

| Line | Code | Reasoning |
|---|---|---|
| `import javax.swing.JLabel;` | Imports the JLabel class from Swing package |
| `extends JFrame` | Inherits JFrame so we can directly add components and call `setVisible` |
| `JLabel welcomeLabel = new JLabel("Welcome...")` | Constructs a label with text in a single step (using `JLabel(String)` constructor) |
| `setFont(new Font("Arial", Font.BOLD, 24))` | Font style constant `Font.BOLD` (1) — alternatives: `Font.PLAIN` (0), `Font.ITALIC` (2) |
| `setHorizontalAlignment(SwingConstants.CENTER)` | `CENTER = 0`; could also pass `0` directly, but using the constant is **best practice** for readability and exam marks |
| `setForeground(Color.RED)` | Sets the text color; AWT `Color` class has 13 predefined constants (BLACK, BLUE, CYAN, DARK_GRAY, GRAY, GREEN, LIGHT_GRAY, MAGENTA, ORANGE, PINK, RED, WHITE, YELLOW) |
| `add(welcomeLabel)` | The frame's content pane uses `BorderLayout` by default; without `setHorizontalAlignment(CENTER)`, the label would only occupy the top-center region |
| `setSize(500, 150)` | Width × Height in pixels |
| `setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE)` | Window constant `3` — terminates the JVM on close |
| `setLocationRelativeTo(null)` | `null` argument centers the window on the screen |

