## 3.4 Walkthrough 4: Using JLabel as an Image Display

### Problem Statement
Display a single image (with no text) using `JLabel` scaled to fit a 300×300 region. Include a tooltip and an opaque yellow background.

### Solution Code

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;

public class ImageLabelDemo extends JFrame {
    public ImageLabelDemo() {
        // Step 1: Load image
        ImageIcon originalIcon = new ImageIcon("logo.png");

        // Step 2: Scale the image
        Image scaledImage = originalIcon.getImage()
                                        .getScaledInstance(300, 300, Image.SCALE_SMOOTH);
        ImageIcon scaledIcon = new ImageIcon(scaledImage);

        // Step 3: Create a JLabel with the scaled icon
        JLabel imageLabel = new JLabel(scaledIcon);

        // Step 4: Make the label opaque so background color shows
        imageLabel.setOpaque(true);
        imageLabel.setBackground(Color.YELLOW);

        // Step 5: Center the image in the label
        imageLabel.setHorizontalAlignment(SwingConstants.CENTER);
        imageLabel.setVerticalAlignment(SwingConstants.CENTER);

        // Step 6: Add a tooltip
        imageLabel.setToolTipText("Our company logo");

        add(imageLabel);
        setTitle("JLabel as Image Display");
        setSize(400, 400);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setVisible(true);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new ImageLabelDemo();
    }
}
```

### Analytical Matrix

| Step | Code | Reasoning |
|---|---|---|
| `getScaledInstance(300, 300, Image.SCALE_SMOOTH)` | Uses bilinear-style scaling for smoother quality than `SCALE_FAST` or `SCALE_DEFAULT` |
| `setOpaque(true)` | **Required** to see the background color — by default `JLabel` is transparent |
| `setHorizontalAlignment(CENTER)` | Centers the icon in the label's drawing area |
| `setToolTipText("...")` | Provides descriptive hover information (a11y best practice) |

