## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

### 2.1 Operational Logic — The "How" Behind Every JButton

A `JButton` works in **three coordinated phases**, each of which maps directly to marks in KTU theory questions.

**Phase 1 — Instantiation & Configuration**
- An object is allocated on the heap via the `new` keyword.
- Its label, icon, mnemonic, tooltip, alignment, and border are configured **before** the button is added to a container.
- *Why this order?* Modifying visual properties after `add()` triggers unnecessary repaint cycles and can break KTU's `paintComponent()`-based validation questions.

**Phase 2 — Event Subscription (Listener Registration)**
- The button is *registered* with one or more `ActionListener` objects via `addActionListener()`.
- Internally, Swing's `EventDispatchThread (EDT)` stores the listener inside an `EventListenerList` (a `javax.swing` utility class).
- The button does **not** know what the listener will do; it only knows **when** to fire (`fireActionPerformed()`).

**Phase 3 — Event Dispatch & Reaction**
- User action (mouse release inside button bounds) → Swing's `BasicButtonListener` catches the `MouseEvent` → converts it to an `ActionEvent` → the registered `actionPerformed(ActionEvent e)` method is invoked on the EDT.
- The `ActionEvent` carries the **command string** (default: button text) and the **event timestamp**.

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU "Why" Question Trap:** A `JButton` can fire `ActionEvent` even without an `ActionListener` (e.g., via `setActionCommand()` or through a `ButtonModel`). But the listener is what gives the button **functional meaning**. Without it, the button is *visually present* but *semantically dead*.

### 2.2 KTU Constructor Cheat Sheet (High-Yield)

| Constructor | Purpose | When KTU Asks It |
|---|---|---|
| `JButton()` | Creates a button with no text and no icon | Default constructor questions |
| `JButton(String text)` | Creates a button with the given text label | Most common in exam programs |
| `JButton(Icon icon)` | Creates a button displaying only an icon | Image-button questions |
| `JButton(String text, Icon icon)` | Creates a button with both text and icon | Combined UI questions |
| `JButton(Action a)` | Creates a button whose properties are bound to the supplied `Action` object | MVC-pattern questions |

### 2.3 KTU Method Cheat Sheet (Top-Exam-Yield Methods)

| Method Signature | Behavior | KTU Marks Weight |
|---|---|---|
| `void setText(String text)` | Sets the button's label | ★★★ |
| `String getText()` | Returns the current label | ★★ |
| `void setIcon(Icon icon)` | Sets the displayed image | ★★★ |
| `void setMnemonic(int keyCode)` | Sets the Alt-keyboard shortcut | ★★★ |
| `void setEnabled(boolean b)` | Enables/disables the button (grays out if false) | ★★★ |
| `void addActionListener(ActionListener l)` | Registers the event handler | ★★★★ |
| `void removeActionListener(ActionListener l)` | Unregisters a handler | ★ |
| `void setActionCommand(String command)` | Overrides the default command string in the event | ★★ |
| `void doClick()` / `doClick(int pressTime)` | Programmatically simulates a user click | ★★ |
