## 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Since `JButton` is a programming component rather than a pure mathematical entity, the "derivation" below is replaced by an **analytical construction walkthrough** — a stepwise, code-and-explanation breakdown that mirrors KTU's "Write a Java program that..." question style.

### 3.1 Analytical Walkthrough — The "Perfect JButton" Lifecycle

**Step 1 — Import the packages.**
KTU exams often test whether you remember that `JButton` lives in `javax.swing`, while the `ActionListener` interface lives in `java.awt.event`.

$$
\text{import javax.swing.JButton;} \quad \wedge \quad \text{import java.awt.event.ActionListener;}
$$

*Why both?* `JButton` is a Swing (lightweight) component, but its event hierarchy is rooted in AWT's delegation event model.

**Step 2 — Declare the field.**
A button is usually declared as a class-level field (or local variable inside a constructor) so that the listener (often a separate inner class or `this`) can access it.

$$
\text{private JButton submitButton;}
$$

**Step 3 — Instantiate and configure.**
This is where each constructor variant comes into play.

$$
\text{submitButton} = \text{new JButton}(\text{"Submit"});
$$

*Logical mapping:* The string `"Submit"` becomes both the visual label and the default `actionCommand` of any `ActionEvent` fired by this button.

**Step 4 — Apply UI customizations (optional but KTU-favorite).**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{submitButton.setMnemonic(KeyEvent.VK\_S)}; \\
\text{submitButton.setToolTipText}("Click to submit the form"); \\
\text{submitButton.setEnabled(true)};
\end{aligned}
$$

*Why the mnemonic matters:* It allows keyboard accessibility — `Alt + S` triggers the same `ActionEvent` as a mouse click, which is a frequent KTU Part-A conceptual question.

**Step 5 — Register the listener.**
The button is *coupled* to its handler. This is the **Liskov-friendly** portion of OOP — the button does not know what action it performs, only that *something* will be invoked.

$$
\text{submitButton.addActionListener}(\text{this});
$$

If the enclosing class `implements ActionListener`, the `this` reference acts as the listener. Otherwise, an inner class is used.

**Step 6 — Add to a container.**

$$
\text{panel.add(submitButton);} \quad \wedge \quad \text{frame.add(panel);}
$$

*Why a `JPanel` between the button and the `JFrame`?* The frame's `ContentPane` is a `Container` that uses `BorderLayout` by default; a `JPanel` allows flexible layout managers such as `FlowLayout` or `GridLayout`.

**Step 7 — Implement the listener method.**

$$
\text{public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e)} \{ \ldots \}
$$

Inside this method, you branch on `e.getActionCommand()` if multiple buttons share a single listener — a classic KTU mini-project pattern.

### 3.2 Complete KTU-Style Model Program

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class ButtonDemo extends JFrame implements ActionListener {
    JButton b1, b2;
    JLabel label;

    public ButtonDemo() {
        setTitle("KTU JButton Demo");
        setSize(400, 200);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());

        b1 = new JButton("Click Me");
        b1.setMnemonic(KeyEvent.VK_C);  // Alt+C
        b1.setActionCommand("BUTTON_ONE");
        b1.addActionListener(this);

        b2 = new JButton("Reset");
        b2.setEnabled(true);
        b2.setActionCommand("BUTTON_TWO");
        b2.addActionListener(this);

        label = new JLabel("Press a button...");

        add(b1); add(b2); add(label);
        setVisible(true);
    }

    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        String cmd = e.getActionCommand();
        if (cmd.equals("BUTTON_ONE")) {
            label.setText("You clicked Click Me at " + e.getWhen());
        } else if (cmd.equals("BUTTON_TWO")) {
            label.setText("Reset pressed.");
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new ButtonDemo();
    }
}
```

### 3.3 Step-by-Step Execution Trace (for KTU dry-run questions)

1. JVM invokes `main(String[] args)`.
2. `new ButtonDemo()` allocates the frame on the heap.
3. Constructor sets the title, size, layout, and creates two `JButton` objects.
4. `addActionListener(this)` registers the current `ButtonDemo` object in each button's internal `EventListenerList`.
5. `setVisible(true)` schedules a `paint()` call on the EDT.
6. User clicks `b1` → `BasicButtonListener.mouseReleased()` → `AbstractButton.fireActionPerformed()`.
7. The EDT invokes `this.actionPerformed(e)` → `label` is updated.
8. `e.getWhen()` returns a `long` timestamp in milliseconds since the Unix epoch.

