## 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

### Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

**Q1. [KTU University Exam — May 2024]**
*Define `JButton` and list any three of its constructors with their functional roles.*

**Model Answer:**

`JButton` is a Swing component, defined in `javax.swing` package, used to create a clickable push-button in a GUI. It extends `AbstractButton` and supports text, icon, or both as its display content. When clicked, it generates an `ActionEvent`.

Three constructors:
1. `JButton()` — Creates a button with no text or icon.
2. `JButton(String text)` — Creates a button with the specified text label.
3. `JButton(Icon icon)` — Creates a button that displays the given image.

**(3 marks: 1 for definition, 2 for constructors)**

---

**Q2. [KTU University Exam — Dec 2023]**
*Explain the role of the `ActionListener` interface with respect to `JButton`. How is it registered?*

**Model Answer:**

`ActionListener` is an interface from `java.awt.event` package containing a single callback method:

$$
\text{public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e);}
$$

When a `JButton` is clicked (or activated via keyboard/programmatic call), Swing invokes the `actionPerformed` method of every registered `ActionListener`. Registration is done using the `addActionListener(ActionListener l)` method on the button instance.

**(3 marks: 1 for interface, 1 for method, 1 for registration)**

---

### Part B — Full 14-Mark Questions (Internal Choice Pattern)

#### Question A — (14 Marks) [KTU University Exam — July 2024]

**(a)** Write a Java program using Swing that creates a `JFrame` containing two `JButton` objects labeled **"Red"** and **"Blue"**. Implement a **single `ActionListener`** that changes the background color of the frame based on which button is clicked. Use the `setActionCommand()` method to distinguish the buttons. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Explain the inheritance hierarchy of `JButton` in Swing. How does this hierarchy enable polymorphism in event handling? **(7 marks)**

**Model Solution for (a):**

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class ColorChanger extends JFrame implements ActionListener {
    JButton redBtn, blueBtn;

    public ColorChanger() {
        setTitle("Color Changer");
        setSize(300, 200);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());

        redBtn = new JButton("Red");
        redBtn.setActionCommand("RED");
        redBtn.addActionListener(this);

        blueBtn = new JButton("Blue");
        blueBtn.setActionCommand("BLUE");
        blueBtn.addActionListener(this);

        add(redBtn);
        add(blueBtn);
        getContentPane().setBackground(Color.WHITE);
        setVisible(true);
    }

    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        String cmd = e.getActionCommand();
        if (cmd.equals("RED")) {
            getContentPane().setBackground(Color.RED);
        } else if (cmd.equals("BLUE")) {
            getContentPane().setBackground(Color.BLUE);
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new ColorChanger();
    }
}
```

*Explanation:* Both buttons share a single `ActionListener` (the `ColorChanger` frame itself). `setActionCommand("RED")` and `setActionCommand("BLUE")` assign unique identifiers, and `e.getActionCommand()` is used inside `actionPerformed()` to dispatch behavior. **(7 marks: 1 imports, 1 class declaration, 2 UI setup, 1 listener registration, 2 logic)**

**Model Solution for (b):**

`JButton` belongs to the following hierarchy:

$$
\text{Object} \rightarrow \text{Component} \rightarrow \text{Container} \rightarrow \text{JComponent} \rightarrow \text{AbstractButton} \rightarrow \text{JButton}
$$

- **`Component`** provides painting, sizing, and event infrastructure.
- **`Container`** allows the button to be added to other containers.
- **`JComponent`** adds Swing-specific features like borders, tooltips, and pluggable look-and-feel.
- **`AbstractButton`** centralizes the model (`ButtonModel`), event firing logic, and shared properties (text, icon, mnemonic) used by `JButton`, `JToggleButton`, `JCheckBox`, and `JRadioButton`.

**Polymorphism in event handling:** Because all these button types extend `AbstractButton`, an `ActionListener` registered on any of them triggers the same callback signature. A single listener can handle heterogeneous button families uniformly, satisfying the OOP **Dependency Inversion Principle** — the listener depends on the `ActionListener` abstraction, not on a specific button subclass. **(7 marks: 2 hierarchy, 2 abstraction, 1 polymorphism, 2 principle mapping)**

---

#### Question B — (14 Marks) [KTU University Exam — Dec 2023]

**(a)** Write a Java Swing program that creates a `JButton` with **both an icon and text**. The button should be enabled to use the **mnemonic 'S'** and should display a **tooltip "Click to submit"**. On clicking, it must show a `JOptionPane` message dialog confirming the click. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Differentiate between `setEnabled(false)` and `removeActionListener()` on a `JButton`. When would you use each in a real application? **(7 marks)**

**Model Solution for (a):**

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class SubmitButtonDemo extends JFrame implements ActionListener {
    JButton submit;

    public SubmitButtonDemo() {
        setTitle("Submit Demo");
        setSize(400, 200);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());

        ImageIcon icon = new ImageIcon("submit.png");
        submit = new JButton("Submit", icon);
        submit.setMnemonic('S');
        submit.setToolTipText("Click to submit");
        submit.addActionListener(this);

        add(submit);
        setVisible(true);
    }

    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        if (e.getSource() == submit) {
            JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(this, "Form submitted successfully!");
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new SubmitButtonDemo();
    }
}
```

*Key points:* `JButton(String, Icon)` constructor applies both label and image. `setMnemonic('S')` binds `Alt+S`. `setToolTipText(...)` provides hover-help. `e.getSource()` identifies the source button before responding. **(7 marks)**

**Model Solution for (b):**

| Aspect | `setEnabled(false)` | `removeActionListener()` |
|---|---|---|
| **Visual Effect** | Button is grayed out and non-clickable | Button looks normal and remains clickable |
| **Event Firing** | No `ActionEvent` is fired at all | `ActionEvent` is fired but no listener receives it |
| **Re-enabling** | Trivial — call `setEnabled(true)` | Requires re-adding the listener |
| **Use Case** | Conditional UI logic (e.g., disable "Pay" until cart is filled) | Permanent decoupling (e.g., remove a "Logout" listener after session expiry) |

**Application Scenario:** A **login form** uses `setEnabled(false)` on the "Submit" button until both username and password fields are non-empty. In contrast, an **admin panel** may use `removeActionListener()` to detach a "Delete" action after the delete operation completes, preventing accidental re-trigger. **(7 marks: 2 contrast points, 2 visual, 3 application)**

---

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Pitfall — Where Students Commonly Lose Marks**
> 1. **Forgetting `setDefaultCloseOperation(EXIT_ON_CLOSE)`** — KTU deducts 0.5 mark for the window-not-closing behavior (a classic observability loss in Swing programs).
> 2. **Using `==` for string comparison on `getActionCommand()`** — Always use `.equals()`; string comparison with `==` is a **2-mark penalty**.
> 3. **Adding the listener *after* the button is removed from the UI** — Listener registration must happen on a live, container-attached button.
> 4. **Confusing `setMnemonic(int)` with `setMnemonic(char)`** — The method takes an `int` (a `KeyEvent.VK_*` constant), but KTU accepts `char` due to implicit conversion; consistency is key.
> 5. **Not invoking `setVisible(true)` last** — Swing components must be configured *before* visibility to avoid re-render penalties and visual flicker.

